Spectacular jump in "wingsuit" over Bogota
Sportsman Jhonathan Florez jumped Thursday from a helicopter over Bogota, the Colombian capital.
Equipped with a wingsuit (a combination equipped with wings), it went up to 160 km/h above the famous Monserrate Sanctuary, located at more than 3,000 meters above sea level, where many bastards had gathered to observe its exploit.
A black box in your car?
While planners in the U.S. road network find it difficult to find the money to repair the deprecated highway infrastructure, many are looking for a solution in the form of a small black box that attaches itself to the dashboard of your car.
The aircraft, which records all miles travelled by a motorist and transmits information to public servants, are at the centre of a controversial attempt in Washington and in the planning government offices to reshape the obsolete system of financing major American roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of major axis planning suddenly led to a lively debate and turbulent alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to pressure the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you travel, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is down.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress are unable to agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay according to the number of miles travelled.
Thousands of motorists have already embarked these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS surveillance system, for an experimental trip.
This is truly indispensable for our nation.
"It's not like we have a choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, general manager of the Southern California Association of Governments, who says the state is starting to record the miles travelled by each Californian motorist by 2025.
There's going to be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is there to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, financed with taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The gas tax is simply not tenable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed tracers on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
"It turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long term," he said.
Wonks calls this from user fees to mileage.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces the urban Liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system because they are developing strategies to achieve the goals set out in the ambitious state laws on global warming.
But representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), Chair of the Transport Committee of the House of Representatives, said that he also considered it the most viable alternative in the long term.
Supporters of the Reason Foundation's free market also appreciate the idea of making drivers pay per mile.
"It's not just a tax in a big black hole," said Adrian Moore, Vice President of Politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transport Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move towards payment by mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have covered approximately 10,000 cars.
But the Speaker of the House killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several States and major cities are making progress.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country's largest experience.
These motorists will soon pay the state kilometric fees instead of gas taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And coalition I-95, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transportation in states along the American east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is exploring how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their cars with a device, drivers were concerned that the government would be able to follow their every move.
"The concerns about Big Brother and that kind of thing are a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, who leads strategic performance management in Nevada's Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the start of the trial, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site: "It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged localization devices."
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily goings and comings.
Nevada is among the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact place or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to use a small start-up in California called True Mileage.
Initially, the company was not intended to assist motorists who pay taxes to the states.
It sought to break into the emerging auto insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices it tests were popular with major axis planners because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't register their speed and locate them," said Ryan Morrison, True Mileage's Managing Director.
Major mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less costly means and far less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experiment by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles travelled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transport officials are seeking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide "driving payment" insurance, and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers them," said a document on urban development.
However, some transport planners wonder whether the whole debate on mile payment is not simply a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission of the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say that Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by increasing gas taxes.
An additional single or annual tax could be imposed on hybrid drivers and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
"It is not necessary to resort to radical surgery when you simply need aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, Director of Legislation and Public Affairs at the Commission.
If we do this, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four Unreleased Listening
The English musician has not finished surprising this year.
Starting from The Next Day, released in January, he designed a luxury re-edition scheduled for November 4, with several new releases.
Four have already emerged on the Web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone panicky.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he said that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dates from 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that he could still be counted on to sparkle the pop scene.
A feast for his fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one trick in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke has thus planned to reissue this album on November 4.
For the occasion, he concocted a real feast for his fans.
This re-release, entitled The Next Day Extra, will be presented in the form of three discs: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four previously unveiled clips.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks of the Deluxe edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
It introduces both each record, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and pouches, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, above all, he gives a taste of his new Atomica title, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with very forward guitars and well-controlled rock electricity.
Unpublished already listening
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-sided: a disturbing intro before a light cavalcade that slows down gradually to give way to a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a little reference to Elton John's Rocket Man, or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems in any case in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again refers to his strangeness: would he come from another planet?
The bewitching guitar riffs make you want to leave the Earth.
Bowie has fun playing the chameleon with these titles: alternately informant, man on board a rocket, Martian potential...
He hides and reveals at once, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, notably with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
Nothing surprising that he had a mask in his hand in the photograph of the campaign L'Invitation au Voyage, of the brand Louis Vuitton, whose new face he embodies.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that injured soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was followed by all soldiers before their return to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and the New Democrats in the House of Commons, Mr.Nicholson assured that before their release, members of the army were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All injured soldiers receive appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them are released until they are ready, he said.
Detractors accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured military personnel - who do not meet the "universal service" rule of the army requiring staff to be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
In particular, they cited two cases reported by La Presse Canadienne, including that of a soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a reservist from London, Ontario, suffering from post-traumatic stress disorder, was released from the military despite his request to remain for another year in order to receive a fully indexed retirement.
His case occurred after Corporal Glen Kirkland, who told a parliamentary committee last month that he had been pushed out before being ready because he did not meet the rule of universality of service.
Mr. Hawkins pointed out that a soldier could be prepared to leave, with plans and consultation sessions, but that it was totally different than wanting to leave the ranks.
"I told them I wasn't ready," he said in an interview with La Presse Canadienne on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was a way I could stay, and they said no.
Since the beginning of the major fighting in Afghanistan, the army has been struggling to determine what latitude it can give to injured soldiers who want to remain in the ranks, but who are not fit for combat.
Under current rules, seriously injured soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for overseas deployments, they may be forced to leave the army.
Data presented to Parliament last year indicate that of the 1,218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the required length of service to obtain retirement benefits.
Liberal veteran spokesman Jim Karygiannis called Wednesday for Corporal Hawkins to be reinstated, while NDP Jack Harris called for an immediate end to "this shameful practice."
