Snowden is ready to "cooperate" with Germany on the issue of U.S. surveillance
Edward Snowden, the U.S. intelligence service whistleblower, said he was willing to go to Berlin to testify before the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander did not provide answers on their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he enjoys the right of asylum, to discuss his testimony in Germany.
In a letter that the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, Mr Snowden said: "Although the result of my efforts was obviously positive, my government continues to treat the difference of opinion as a leak and seeks to penalise political discourse with accusations against which it is impossible to defend itself."
However, telling the truth is not a crime.
In his letter, Mr. Snowden wrote that he believed that the support of the international community could persuade the US government to drop the criminal charges against him.
As part of the complaint filed by the U.S. Department of Justice, he is charged with espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, German Interior Minister, told Zeit Online: "If Mr Snowden is ready to speak to German officials, we will make this possible."
Relations between the United States and Germany have been strained by complaints that the NSA had tapped the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Thomas Oppermann, the deputy who heads the parliamentary group overseeing the foreign secret services, said that if there was a chance to hear Mr. Snowden as a witness "without endangering him and completely ruining relations with the United States," it was necessary to take advantage of it.
Mr Ströbele, German Green MEP, published a photo of him with Mr Snowden on his Twitter account.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Ströbele stated that, according to counsel for the former NSA consultant, Mr. Snowden could not return to Russia if he left the country.
If Mr. Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would have to be assured that he would be "safe" there, the MP said.
Mr. Snowden wrote in his letter that he had been subjected to a "serious and sustained" persecution campaign that forced him to leave his country.
However, he said that he had been encouraged by the global response to “my act of political expression”.
Citizens from all over the world, as well as senior officials – including in the United States – considered the disclosure of an inexplicable system of permanent surveillance to be of public benefit.
The letter puts forward an offer of cooperation with the German authorities "when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved".
