Frontier Airlines plans to charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers carrying hand luggage on its flights up to $100.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although in its announcement on Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them when the aircraft descended.
The new hand luggage charges are for bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free of charge.
Frontier stated that it would charge $25 if the charges were paid in advance and $100 if the passengers only paid once at the boarding gate.
Frontier's spokesperson, Kate O'Malley, indicated that the $100 was intended to encourage travellers to pay the fees in advance.
"We don't want to charge this price," she explained.
Airlines began charging for the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid these charges put as much as they could in the carry-on baggage stowed in the upper compartments, so there was often no room in these compartments.
These charges are a way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley stated that these new fees will not really be used to raise money.
It is a matter of making the most loyal Frontier customers understand that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find room in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their tickets on the airline's website will not have to pay.
For example, a passenger queued at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and registration procedures are changing to ensure that passengers are aware of these charges before arriving at the door.
Frontier's hand luggage costs will not be applied until the summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often blush about baggage and other expenses, but airlines love them.
They believe that the cost of handling baggage is significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street consider the addition of baggage charges as a sign that airlines charge enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of loss.
However, many of them did not pay the baggage costs.
Spirit Airlines Inc. applied the first carry-on charges three years ago, and the low-cost Allegiant company followed a little later.
The only other company imposing such charges is the Hungarian company Wizz Air, said the consultant to airlines Jay Sorensen, who closely follows the extra charges.
In a December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit's hand luggage costs were $50 million per year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines manager, recently travelled on Spirit and wondered what he was going to find at the boarding gate when passengers discovered the unusual carry-on charges imposed by the company.
"I've never seen such a fluid boarding process in my entire career," he said.
I expected to see teeth gnashing and a fight at the door.
The aircraft was full, he added, "the passengers boarded at the speed of the lightning."
Frontier also makes as Spirit and applies a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier indicated that passengers who take a soda or fruit juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who take coffee can be served free of charge.
It will always distribute water free of charge.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for drinks in 2008 but went back seven months after the passengers complained and no other major airline had followed.
Frontier's decision to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not purchase their tickets directly from the airline is his last attempt to encourage customers to go to his site.
Airlines pay online travel vendors like Orbitz $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This prompted all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of contacting an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, it began to offer only half of the loyalty miles to customers who bought their ticket via an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she reduced mile bonuses by 25% on a trip.
For example, a 1,000-mile Frontier trip purchased from an online travel agency would save 250 miles.
It also allows passengers to choose their seats in advance only if they buy their tickets directly from the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal clientele in its home town, Denver, but its business is shrinking and it is losing money.
Revenues dropped by 9% and its flight capacity decreased by almost 13% in the first quarter, according to financial results released on Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic tried to correct Frontier's finances by selling the airline.
NSA calls into question an "internal error" and not hackers for the breakdown of its site
The National Security Agency working in the shadows said on Friday that it was a bug that caused its public site to fail for a few hours, not hackers as some claimed it was online.
"NSA.gov remained inaccessible for a few hours this evening due to an internal error that occurred during a planned update," the espionage agency said in an email statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
The allegations that the breakdown was due to a distributed denial of service attack [DSD] are false.
Earlier this evening, online server trackers noted that the NSA site had been down for at least 6 hours, and some users still cannot access the site.
Earlier, an NSA spokesperson told ABC News that the agency's sensitive internal network was "not at all" compromised.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesperson explained.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed to be responsible for the breakdown of the NSA site by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses.
Cyber-tactic is not very sophisticated and attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
The once ultra-secret NSA, a time known as the "No Such Agency", has come under the spotlight and has been heavily criticized in recent months as a result of a wave of revelations about its extensive national and foreign communications surveillance programs – which are part of the NSA's secret files stolen from the agency and disclosed by NSA's disillusioned former consultant, Edward Snowden.
This growing controversy around the agency has led to many speculations that tonight's incident was the result of a targeted cyber-operation.
The Delta Downtown now closed
The Delta Centre-Ville hotel closed on Thursday in Montreal, after 36 years of existence.
The investment fund that owned the building sold it to developers who will turn it into student residences.
Three hundred and fifty people worked at the hotel.
Of these, 200 have still not found a new job.
Delta promises not to let down his employees.
Employers came to meet with employees directly on site, and employees were met individually to assess their needs.
"This support will continue for the next six months," explains the Regional Director of Labour Relations at Delta Hotels, Félix Bisson.
The Delta is closed in a highly competitive hotel market.
The investment fund that owned that building had choices to make.
Either he was reinvesting in the building to continue operating it, so there were investments of tens of millions while the competition is very fierce, there are many new hotels that appeared in Montreal.
"Or he was selling it to someone else and that's what happened," explains Paul Arsenault, Chair of Transat Tourism at the UQAM School of Management Sciences.
