Bombardier's profit is down, while aircraft deliveries and orders are down
Bombardier Inc., a Canadian aircraft and rail manufacturer, reported a 15% drop in net profit on Thursday, driven by lower orders and deliveries of aircraft during the third quarter and contractual problems in its Trains division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, did not provide flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft, nor did it provide information on whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious commercial commissioning schedule by September.
After the inaugural flight of the test aircraft about a month and a half ago, the pilot flew only three times, and the question then arose as to whether the test phase was on track.
The results did not match the forecast and the share price fell by 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his rating on Thursday from "overperformance" to "sector performance" due to the low potential for stock exchange growth in the next quarter or two quarters.
"Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was largely anticipated, we are truly disappointed with the profit margin in the Transport division," Cameron Doerksen said in a customer note.
We expect Bombardier to register new orders for its CSeries aircraft as the flight test program moves forward.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more sceptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will be able to catapult it into the lower segment of a market now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delay.
But the number of firm orders for CSeries aircraft has so far been modest at 177. It seems that potential buyers are waiting for the results of the flight tests to validate the company's assertions about the energy efficiency and savings potential of the new airliner.
At present, the company has registered a total of 403 purchase orders and commitments with 15 customers and operators.
Pierre Beaudoin, President and Chief Executive Officer, is confident that Bombardier will reach its target of 300 firm orders prior to the commercial commissioning of the first aircraft.
Leaders also reassured analysts and the media on Thursday that the program was progressing in line with the schedule.
"The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," said Mr. Beaudoin at a conference call, adding that ground testing and software updates were planned during the aircraft's downtime.
Each manufacturer plans differently.
We had decided to proceed to a first flight and to schedule an update period, and that's what we did.
This will happen again throughout the flight program.
The second of the five test aircraft is expected to fly in the coming weeks, the others will follow shortly thereafter, said the company.
However, analysts are skeptical that the first customer can fly a CSeries aircraft only 12 months after its inaugural flight.
