Police officers spotted Sarborough, 32 years old, dropping three bags of cocaine at the lawyer's home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was attending a bar dinner with confreres.
Investigations revealed that Ditta was a "regular consumer" of this Class A drug after tests showed traces of cocaine in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Over an eight-month period between January and August 2011, he sought unlawfully to obtain information about the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his associates.
The four suspects were then monitored by police as part of a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire counties.
Together with 32 other men, they were subsequently imprisoned after the police seized heroin and cocaine for £1.5 million, as well as over £200,000 in cash during a series of raids.
Ditta, 42, provided information to criminals because he feared that his drug addiction would be revealed in the open.
Today, in Liverpool's Assize Court, Ditta, who works in Blackburn's Forbes Solicitors law firm, has fallen into disgrace after being convicted on two counts of obstructing justice after a three-week trial.
He admitted possession of cocaine in a previous hearing.
The fall of the lawyer occurred after the police, investigating Scarborough, discovered that he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two investigators followed the suspect and spotted him arriving at Ditta's home and placing drugs, 60 per cent pure, under the lawyer's trash cans in a black golf glove.
Shortly after the deposit, Scarborough was in regular telephone contact with Ditta who was at a dinner at the Ewood Park football stadium, home of the Blackburn Rovers club.
The lawyer went home, found out about the drugs, and they called nine times.
The court heard that Ditta was a "regular user" of cocaine after tests showed traces of this Class A drug in her hair, on her wallet and on her credit cards.
Ditta was arrested later but denied using cocaine. He stated that he had spoken to the alleged drug dealer because he was his client and argued that their discussions were subject to a "legal privilege".
During his arrest, Ditta collected his wallet and attempted to withdraw several credit cards, but they were all seized and a hair sample was taken from him.
During an interrogation, he stated that he had an office at his home, as well as at his place of work, and that sometimes clients called him at his home for legal matters.
But the court heard testimony that he was calling major players in the drug trade, some of whom he had represented, after key arrests to tell them which investigators were aware of.
Prosecutor Anne Whyte said: "If anyone should know that the law should not be violated, he is indeed a criminal lawyer."
Mr. Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal lawyer, and of too much involvement with particular clients.
The relationship we're talking about is not just a drug dealer, but a drug dealer providing drugs to his own lawyer.
Some of his communications will undoubtedly be legitimate communications because he was his lawyer.
But it went far beyond the ordinary limits of a relationship between a lawyer and his client.
He obstructed the investigation of the police as much as he could to enable him to continue his criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta did not honour his profession, but dishonored it.
He has been too close to some clients, particularly Scarborough, and has allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta denied any illegal action and said, "If I was a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and if I had wanted to provide information to Mr. Scarborough, I would not have waited 3 p.m., I would have done so immediately."
But after the hearing, Superintendent Lee Halstead of the Lancashire Police said: "Mr. Ditta went from a criminal lawyer to a criminal himself when he started getting drugs from criminal organizations."
His addiction to cocaine has compromised him forever and made him vulnerable to the ulterior motives of the leading members of organized criminal groups who tasked him with obtaining valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers should observe the strictest rules of integrity and create a climate of trust among the public.
Mr. Ditta betrayed this trust and tried to hide behind the varnish of his profession.
The serious and organized crime unit in Lancashire conducted the investigation into Mr. Ditta, who was found guilty of the three counts of possession of cocaine and now obstructing justice, testifying to his commitment to prosecute criminals.
