A report submitted to the European Commission in 2011 described intersex persons as different from transgender or transgender persons, since their status is not related to sex but rather to their biological constitution, which is neither exclusively that of a man nor exclusively that of a woman, but is generally both at the same time and not clearly defined as either.
These characteristics can manifest themselves in secondary sexual traits (such as muscle mass, hairiness, chest and stature), primary sexual traits (such as reproductive organs and sexual organs) or chromosome structure and hormones.
The report also provided an overview of the discrimination faced by intersex and transgender persons in employment, as well as the extent of harassment, violence and prejudice-motivated crimes.
