When these children were born, the psychiatrist was not called, and the surgeon was called.
The dominant theory on how to treat children with ambiguous sexual organs was initiated by Dr. John Money of Johns-Hopkins University, who considered the gender to be malleable.
He stated the term "sexual identity" and argued that social and environmental signals – the way parents raise a child – interact with a child's genes and hormones to shape it so that it is identified as male or female.
