Not all wage freezes in the world will prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is rumbling, particularly in France, one of the leading leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport of its political legitimacy and imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the French economy struggling.
As a result, Marine Le Pen's far-right party, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, returning the socialists to power in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split from the right will automatically favour the left.
What does Marine Le Pen do with his new popularity with the French white working class?
It wants to use next year's European elections to create a single anti-European anti-currency bloc in the European Parliament.
