But in its opening statement to the Commission, the YMCA stated that it "had never had to deal with a problem of sexual assault on children within its organization."
Director General Phillip Hare was questioned in two cases: one YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences and a physical education instructor from the YMCA Caringbah Hall was found guilty of child sexual assault in the centre where he worked in 1991.
Mr. Hare told Gail Furness, counsel to the Commission, that he was aware of the first case but was not aware of the second.
He also admitted that the YMCA's opening statement was inaccurate, noting, "external monitoring of the YMCA was carried out and indicated that the safety of children was a top priority for the organization."
It was demonstrated to the Commission that the YMCA had been informed that it had received the second worst ratings on four institutions in an audit of the Department of Education and Communities carried out in August this year.
Mr. Hare, who began working at the YMCA at the age of 21, admitted that personnel management was a failure with Lord's recruitment and failed to verify that employees knew they were required to report any violations of the child safety policy.
