Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presented Danse Danse with her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by Henri Michaux's inks and poems, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from ink black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, advances, in profile, fine as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple trait, takes its shape.
And this form will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of drawings.
The dancers, entirely dressed in black, only the hands and face discovered, wait on either side of the playing area, rush when the next print appears, incarnate it, come out running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done in relay of solos, in group in unison (a mass that is solo), in large group of twelve solos where each executes his sign.
One thinks of "Gloire du matin", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, posed online at the forestage.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is strong, percussions and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the rhythm is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux' poem, monocord and monotonous in the cry, and will continue while dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to take over.
This loud and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up softening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a force at Chouinard - such as those hairs that fade or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux' work, has established herself with her tics.
As a result, the bodies seem flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a broader and gibby imagination than dance, more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theatre, touches magic.
The audience liked it, the welcome was warm.
The Gymnopedias, after the intermission, are richer.
The scene is partly draped with grey, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in a forsaken house.
At the piano, dancers take turns playing the scores.
Their clumsiness in music, touching, gives a real fragility.
On stage, spend couples, in romantic duets, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffoons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, with a red nose, in very polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnassier, fuyant or gambler.
The gesture, the laughs and the little cries perfectly transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridicule of the bodies into coitus, of the beings that merge.
But the play takes off after salvation.
A clown comes back on stage when the audience leaves.
Here, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the universes explored overlap, the dancers cabotinate, descend among the spectators, glove, smoke, short-circuit, play the codes of applause, spread the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
The joy and folly transpire, and it is Chouinard's art, there, to contaminate the audience.
