John Kerry admitted, unprecedentedly, that American espionage "had gone too far inappropriately"
John Kerry pointed out that the defensive attitude of the United States vis-à-vis its surveillance programs had been softened by the fact that on several occasions espionage had "been too far away inappropriately."
The Secretary of State also admitted that he had, like Barack Obama, ruled on "automatic pilot" when a series of incendiary revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA's spying activities came into being.
The leaks put the U.S. government at the centre of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have learned of certain things in autopilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War and until the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course on September 11."
He then became the first senior member of the U.S. government to admit that American espionage had gone beyond bounds, but insisted that everyone's rights had not been violated.
He said: "In some cases, it went too far inappropriately."
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make clear to people that he is now undertaking a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels wrong.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for the good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: "We live in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up."
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We have indeed prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we were able to get to know the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. legislators will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged American espionage case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the U.S., the Chair of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut indicated that he had spoken to the members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made to a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations because of the feeling of frustration generated by the monitoring of the National Security Agency.
"It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans remain at our side in the mutual commitment to the fight against terrorism," said Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and Chair of the American Senate's European Affairs Subcommittee, during a meeting from Washington.
And I will go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger caused by the NSA programmes.
The press reports that the NSA has received millions of communications in Europe, which has undermined relations with some US allies, but the director of the agency said this week that it was inaccurate and that this was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the United States.
Other revelations reported documents disclosed by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and those of 34 other Heads of State.
The Director of Intelligence Services, James Clapper, justified allied espionage by indicating that it was necessary and common practice on both sides.
In this tumultuous atmosphere, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a Congress trip, scheduled to take place this year, and that he hoped that the delegation would include members of both parties and the two chambers.
The names of other participating legislators should be announced in the coming days.
He indicated that the route still needs to be defined.
Murphy stated that the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show "feeling firm."
He explained that European heads of state must be honest with their citizens about the type of espionage programmes they have been implementing themselves for years.
"We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world to do espionage," said Murphy.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry has planned to visit the Middle East and Poland this weekend to manage the resentment generated by American strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as by United States surveillance activities.
