Australian woman appeals her sentence of imprisonment in Thailand
A 21-year-old resident of Sydney, sentenced to 15 days' imprisonment in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been assaulted by a taxi driver, appealed the judgement and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was first found guilty by a Phuket Provincial Court on 15 June of false statements after telling the Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who controlled her, had assaulted her early on Sunday, 10 June.
However, videotapes later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket's police interviewed Bamford for two days before she confessed to having invented the story of all the pieces.
She was detained in a cell at the local police station before the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days' imprisonment in a low-security detention centre on the outskirts of Phuket rather than in a women's prison.
This is the daughter of former Australian Rugby League player Peter Tunks, who called on Canberra's Foreign Ministry to help her daughter.
Tunks told Sydney's Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was "extremely concerned" about her daughter's well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
"Of course, we have had an agonizing moment, but we hope to take her home safely as soon as possible," said Tunks.
Bamford appealed the judgement and was released after the bail of 50,000 baht.
In Australia, the press said that in the meantime, she was on vacation in the Krabi region, south of Thailand.
Thai judicial sources indicated that Bamford was represented by a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could lead to an increase in the sentence of up to two years' imprisonment and imprisonment in an adult prison.
However, after the recent murder in Phuket of Michelle Smith, an Australian travel agent, Thailand could also seek to restore its damaged image to tourists, which could lead to acquittal.
